<br>
Every single president...has uttered the phrase &quot;so help me god&quot; at the end of their oath of office.<br>
<br>
Every single legal immigrant to this country has finished their oath of allegiance...with...you guessed it...&quot;so help me god&quot;</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Just another point about these &quot;arguements&quot; ...<br>
<br>
Children aren't being asked to pledge to god in these cases outside of the supervision of their parents. A child isn't president, no matter how childish I think some of them are. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  A child isn't immigrating on their own. And, a child isn't in court without his parents or a proxy to act on their behalf. But, a child is in school and has to have the mental capacity to stand up and say &quot;No&quot; to a teacher when it comes to the pledge. <br>
<br>
Adults can make the decision ... children are the issue here and they don't always have the ability to object to authority the way we do. So, just the pledge saying &quot;Under God&quot; is not inherently bad, but when schools are having it said every morning then it becomes a problem since children, at younger ages, lack the mental structure to be so forward as to object to the pledge's wording and be able to explain to the teacher why. At that age I would have just gone along with the crowd and not made waves no matter what law said the schools couldn't force me to say it.<br>
<br>
This is the ultimate problem ... if its people at a company then the adults can make decisions on their own with 20 years of experience and the capacity for higher reasoning. Kids of 5-15 years old don't exactly have the mental capacity to fully understand what's going on and why, or if, they should object.<br>
<br>
If they can't change the pledge then take the pledge out of schools totally ... or have the schools only use a modified pledge ... or something so there is no pressure on kids to be the ones on the front lines of this debate. <p><a href=http://home.thezone.net/~dhill/fdor.htm><image src=http://home.thezone.net/~dhill/Fdor.jpg></a></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#F5F5DC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/bprexus95980.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=sienea>Sienea</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 3<br> <font color=#FF0000>(7/2/02 2:40:32 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fprexus95980general.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=17260.topic&index=402>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Pledge of Allegiance declared unconstitutional</span><hr size=1> I look at it like this.<br>
<br>
(Brief note, I'm very much Agnostic)<br>
<br>
Here is the perfect example.<br>
<br>
Christmas, originally, the celebration of the birth of Christ (Nowadays it's just a commercial holliday but that's besides the point) Everyone put's christmas decorations up, angels, mangers, and the like. Out for everyone to see. Now...let's look at the other end of the spectrum. Someone who believes in Satan instead of God. If that person ever put the kind of decorations that accompany that faith out on their front lawn, they'd force him to take it down and/or possibly arrest him (depending on which state the person is in).<br>
<br>
I have to ask myself why? That person isn't doing anything the Christmas people are doing, just celebrating his religion. He probably finds all the Christmas decorations just as unbereable as everyone else finds his. Yet, no one forces everyone else to take down their angles and mangers, or consider them crazy for believing in something they have never seen nor have any proof of. Which is all the guy who believes in Satan is doing.<br>
<br>
To me, it's just hypocritical. I don't see why it should even matter what a person believes in, if Joe Schmoe down the street wants to believe that Gary the Gopher created the universe, more power to him. Why label him as mentaly insane for believing that when the billions of people that believe in something that they've never seen (At least Gary the Gopher was tangible) are labeled sane.<br>
<br>
There's a serious problem in this country and it will eventually backfire on us all, I just hope I'm still around for that momentous day. <p><img src="http://www.damn-skippy.org/images/sieneab.gif"></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/uklark.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Klark</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_cyanspot.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 221<br> <font color=#FF0000>(7/2/02 4:38:25 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fprexus95980general.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=17260.topic&index=403>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.twilightcouncil.com/sigs/tc5.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Pledge of Allegiance declared unconstitutional</span><hr size=1> &quot;Adults can make the decision ... children are the issue here and they don't always have the ability to object to authority the way we do. &quot;<br>
