I think the point has been sidetracked. No where does the constitution allow for the maturity of adults over the maturity of children. If you are going to argue that the pledge defines a respect for an established religion, then you cannot take into question the audience. Either it does or it does not.<br>
<br>
And, the intent has been twisted to suit the argument of those against the G-word. Basically, an authority figure saying the oath. If a person (including a child) is watching a court or a congress or a president use a pledge to a higher being does not that fill the case of an authority figure saying the oath. If a president says &quot;And I thank God for being elected&quot; or &quot;I trust in God to protect this nation&quot; and a child watches that on TV, is that not as bad?<br>
<br>
Remember, parents raise children, not schools.  <p>Klark Loampounder <BR>
