<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> I think the point has been sidetracked. No where does the constitution allow for the maturity of adults over the maturity of children. If you are going to argue that the pledge defines a respect for an established religion, then you cannot take into question the audience. Either it does or it does not.</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
I don't think the point is sidetracked at all. I'm just refuting the statements by some people who say &quot;you can just leave God out of it if you're not christian&quot;. Not all people, especially children, have the emotional and mental capacity to stand out of the crowd and say &quot;I won't say the God part&quot;. And, this is where the entire case is coming from. Its not enough for the courts, imo, to say &quot;can't force the kids to say the pledge&quot; because the schools aren't exactly being progressive in this manner. They're continuing to say the pledge unless someone objects ... and who's the person who has to object? A kid. A kid that doesn't really understand these concepts yet. No matter what a parent says to the child he probably doesn't have the mental capacity to grasp the concepts yet. Maybe the courts need to make a stronger assertion and say that the schools shouldn't be reciting the pledge, at all, until later grades when the kids can actually understand the concepts involved. Prior to that its just, frankly, a very mild form of brainwashing in getting them to repeat it over and over again every day.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> And, the intent has been twisted to suit the argument of those against the G-word. Basically, an authority figure saying the oath. If a person (including a child) is watching a court or a congress or a president use a pledge to a higher being does not that fill the case of an authority figure saying the oath. If a president says &quot;And I thank God for being elected&quot; or &quot;I trust in God to protect this nation&quot; and a child watches that on TV, is that not as bad?</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
But, just seeing it once in a court, or once on TV, is not the same as having to listen to it EVERY single day in schools and maybe reciting it themselves for fear of causing trouble by objecting. One is a one-time thing ... the other is a daily indoctrination into the concept that &quot;God&quot; is somehow protecting the USA.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Remember, parents raise children, not schools. </b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Then the schools shouldn't be repeating the pledge every morning and making references to the USA being &quot;under God&quot;. If its up to the schools to raise their children and only the jobs of the schools to educate ... then keep the schools out of things like pledges and religious messages, no matter how vague. Can't have it both ways. Why, afterall, is there a need to force the parents to come into conflict with the schools over the pledge in the first place? Why must the parents and kids stand up to the regular school procedure just so the kid isn't saying things that are against his religious beliefs every morning?<br>
<br>
Take the pledge out of the school totally. Let the parents who believe the pledge should be said every morning have their kids say it before they leave the house. People who object to the pledge can not have their kids say it and those who like the plege can say it morning, noon, and night for all anyone else cares. But, imo, I don't think that's going to fly at all with most people because they honestly want the pledge said in every school every morning ... and if the non-judeo-christians don't want to say the &quot;under God&quot; part ... by &quot;god&quot; they'll hear it said by others. I think Eisenhower said what some people won't say today .... &quot;we'll make sure every school child is speaking the message of the almighty every day&quot; or something along those lines. They wanted to push the concept of Christianity on every child ... every day ... and that's why they changed the pledge in the first place. <br>
<br>
But, instead of going the route of removing the pledge from schools and letting parents decide for themselves they're actually pushing for MORE mandatory legislation. In February a bunch of states pushed for more mandatory reciting of the pledge. One school board that voted against it got backlash for not forcing kids to say the pledge every single day ... to the point that they changed their vote. Not just that, but many states are deciding to post &quot;In God We Trust&quot; on big signs in the schools. More and more religious messages and demands for patriotism from kids who're way too young to even understand the concepts. As I said, its mild brainwashing, its not patriotistm. You ask for patriotism from adults, you don't ask that kids too young to understand the concepts recite a pledge every morning. Well, you don't unless you're more interested in breeding a new brand of patriots and christians than you are in educating kids to make choices for themselves. <p><a href=http://home.thezone.net/~dhill/fdor.htm><image src=http://home.thezone.net/~dhill/Fdor.jpg></a></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/uklark.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Klark</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_cyanspot.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 222<br> <font color=#FF0000>(7/2/02 7:11:39 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fprexus95980general.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=17260.topic&index=405>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.twilightcouncil.com/sigs/tc5.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Pledge of Allegiance declared unconstitutional</span><hr size=1> &quot;One is a one-time thing ... the other is a daily indoctrination into the concept that &quot;God&quot; is somehow protecting the USA.&quot;<br>
